///    Replace with CancellationToken — the cooperative cancellation pattern.
///
/// 2. Thread.ResetAbort() is also gone. No replacement needed since
///    ThreadAbortException can never be thrown.
///
/// 3. ThreadAbortException is effectively dead. Catch OperationCanceledException
///    instead when using cancellation tokens.
///
/// 4. Manual Thread management is replaced with Task + async/await for
///    better resource usage and composability.
///
/// PITFALLS TO WATCH FOR:
/// 
/// - If GetNextItem() is a blocking call (e.g., BlockingCollection.Take()),
///   it will NOT respond to CancellationToken unless you pass the token in.
///   You must change blocking calls to their cancellable overparts (e.g.,
///   BlockingCollection.Take(CancellationToken)) or they'll hang on shutdown.
///
/// - volatile bool _running alone is insufficient for clean shutdown when
///   the thread is blocked. CancellationToken solves this because it can
///   interrupt waits, I/O, and async operations.
///
/// - Don't call _cts.Cancel() inside a finally block that runs on the same
///   task — it can cause subtle reentrancy issues.
///
/// - If ProcessItem() does long CPU work, periodically check
///   token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested() to stay responsive to shutdown.
